# TypeScript & React Standards — pixelAI

## TypeScript

`tsconfig.json` has `strict: true` enabled. All rules below are enforced by the compiler.

### No `any`

Use `unknown` with type narrowing instead of `any`.

```ts
// ✅
function parseConfig(raw: unknown): TransformationConfig {
  if (typeof raw !== "object" || raw === null) throw new Error("Invalid config");
  return raw as TransformationConfig;
}

// ❌
function parseConfig(raw: any) { ... }
```

### Explicit return types on exported functions

```ts
// ✅
export async function getUserImages(userId: string): Promise<Image[]> { ... }

// ❌
export async function getUserImages(userId: string) { ... }
```

### `const` over `let`; `async/await` over `.then()`

```ts
// ✅
const user = await currentUser();

// ❌
let user;
currentUser().then(u => { user = u; });
```

### Type placement

- Co-locate types with the module that owns them
- Shared/global types go in `types/index.d.ts`
- Zod schemas and inferred types go in `schemas/index.ts` — do not inline schemas in components

```ts
// ✅ in schemas/index.ts
export const LoginSchema = z.object({ ... });
export type LoginInput = z.infer<typeof LoginSchema>;
```

## React & Next.js components

### Functional components only

No class components. Use function declarations or arrow functions with explicit `React.FC` typing avoided — prefer typed props interfaces.

```tsx
// ✅
interface HeaderProps {
  title: string;
  subtitle?: string;
}

export const Header = ({ title, subtitle }: HeaderProps) => { ... };

// ❌
class Header extends React.Component { ... }
```

### Named exports

All components use named exports. Default exports are only used where Next.js requires them (page files, layout files, route handlers).

```ts
// ✅ components/shared/Header.tsx
export const Header = () => { ... };

// ❌
export default function Header() { ... }
```

### `"use client"` — minimal usage

Add `"use client"` only when the component uses hooks, browser APIs, or event handlers. Server Components are the default. Check existing files for the pattern before deciding.

### Tailwind class merging

Always use `cn()` from `@/lib/utils` when combining Tailwind classes conditionally.

```tsx
// ✅
import { cn } from "@/lib/utils";
<div className={cn("base-class", isActive && "active-class", className)} />

// ❌
<div className={`base-class ${isActive ? "active-class" : ""}`} />
```

## Forms

All forms use **React Hook Form** with **`zodResolver`**. The reference implementation is `components/shared/TransformationForm.tsx`.

```tsx
// ✅ pattern
const form = useForm<z.infer<typeof MySchema>>({
  resolver: zodResolver(MySchema),
  defaultValues: { ... },
});
```

Use `components/shared/CustomField.tsx` as the wrapper for form fields with `FormField` + `FormControl` from shadcn/ui.

## Server Actions

Server Actions live in `lib/actions/`. They are `async` functions, always wrapped in `try/catch`, and always return a typed result shape.

```ts
// ✅
export async function myAction(data: MyInput): Promise<{ success?: string; error?: string }> {
  try {
    const validated = MySchema.safeParse(data);
    if (!validated.success) return { error: "Invalid input" };
    // ... DB work
    return { success: "Done" };
  } catch (error) {
    handleError(error);
    return { error: "Something went wrong" };
  }
}
```

## shadcn/ui

Never edit files in `components/ui/` directly. They are managed by the shadcn/ui CLI. To customize a component, wrap it in a new file under `components/shared/`.
